ute over who was to\nsucceed Ja'far as Imam led to schism within Shi'a Islam.\nAl-Sadiq was celebrated among his brothers and peers and stood out among them\nfor his great personal merits. He is highly respected by both Sunni\nand Shi'a Muslims for his great Islamic scholarship, pious character, and\nacademic contributions.\n\nShi'a Islamic fiqh, Ja'fari jurisprudence is named after him.The books on\nJa'fari jurisprudence were later written by Muhammad ibn Ya'qub al-Kulayni (864-\n941), Ibn Babawayh (923-991), and Nasir al-Din al-Tusi (1201-1274).\n\nAs well as being considered an Imam of the Shi'a, he is revered by the\nNaqshbandi Sunni Sufi\nchain. [http://www.naqshbandi.org/chain/names.htm]\n\nHe was a polymath: an astronomer, Imam, Islamic scholar, Islamic theologian,\nwriter, philosopher, physician, physicist and scientist. http://alhassanain-\n.com/english/articles/articles/beliefs_library/debates_and_replies/debates_of_i-\nmam_jafar_al_sadiq_a_s/001.html He is also reported to be the teacher of\nthe famous chemist, JÄbir ibn HayyÄn (Geber).\n","linknr":619,"url":"Jafar_al-Sadiq","recorded":1375078000,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Ja%27far_al-Sadiq&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Ja%27far_al-Sadiq&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","/wiki/Ja%27far_al-Sadiq","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.rtlcite%2Cwikihiero%7Cext.uls.nojs%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cskins.vector&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=site&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=startup&only=scripts&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia